    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-01-26T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-01-26T15:00:00-05:00" n="363"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d363">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">396.1 BE/1–2654: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 363<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">United States Delegation at the Berlin
                            Conference</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d363fn1">Repeated to London, Paris, and Moscow.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-01-26T21:00:00+01:00"
                            >January 26, 1954—9 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Secto1">Secto</gloss> 26. Both <persName corresp="#p_EASA1"
                        >Eden</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_BGP1">Bidault</persName> said
                    today that Soviets are going to great lengths to be amiable in their contacts
                    with members of British and French delegations who they are contacting daily.
                    They indicated these Soviet tactics aimed at driving a wedge between the US on
                    one hand and France and UK on other, are transparently clear and in marked
                    contrast to the unconstructive tone and content of <persName corresp="#p_MVM1"
                        >Molotov</persName>’s opening speech.<note n="2" xml:id="d363fn2">Regarding
                            <persName corresp="#p_MVM1">Molotov</persName>’s opening statement, see
                            <gloss target="#t_Secto1">Secto</gloss> 17, <ref target="#d355">Document
                            355</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>This morning <persName corresp="#p_MYA1">Malik</persName> called on <persName
                        corresp="#p_NHA1">Nutting</persName> (UK) and exuded good will. He referred
                    to agenda proposed by <persName corresp="#p_MVM1">Molotov</persName> and blandly
                    said Soviets did not want a long drawn out discussion on the five power
                    conference but just agreement that such a conference would be held.</p>
            </div>
